<h3>cHAPTER 4 cLASSES</h3>
<p> A class is a blueprint from which a object are made. When you are creating a object of a class you are creating a instance of class.</p> 

 

<p>Instance is like a bhoot or ghost which we cannot see or "antar aatma" or precise the good and evil type of people which come when some decision is to be made.</p> 

 

<p>All the code that we write inside in java is inside a class. Java provides wide variety of inbuilt classes which could we used for wide variety of programming like "connection to database", "Connection Google API", File Manipulation, Using Big Data, Using Tensor Flow.. </p> 

 

<p>Still you have to make your own classes according to your application.</p> 

 

<p>Encapsulation (Some time called information hiding) is a key concept in working with object, Formally encapsulation is combining data and behavior in one package and hiding the implementation details from the user of the object. </p><p>The bits of the data in the object are called its instance fields, and the procedures that operate on data are called methods</p> 

 

<p>A specific object which is an instance of a class will have a specific values of its instance fields, The set of the those value is the current state of the object. When you invoke a method the instance field value may change</p> 

 

<p>The key to make encapsulation work is to never directly expose the instance field to other objects. These instance fields can be modified only through methods of that class. Encapsulation is a way to give object its a "black box " feature which is the key to reuse and reusability.</p> 

 

<p>This means a class may totally change how it stores its data, but as long as it continues to use the same methods to manipulate the data, no other object will know or care</p> 
